{"title_page": "Gheorghe Avramescu", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Gheorghe Avramescu\n| image         = Gheorghe Avramescu.jpg\n| caption       = Avramescu in 1945\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1884|01|26|df=yes}}\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1945|03|03|1884|01|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Boto\u0219ani]], [[Boto\u0219ani County]], [[Kingdom of Romania]]\n| death_place  = [[J\u00e1szber\u00e9ny]], [[Kingdom of Hungary]]\n| placeofburial = [[Hajongard cemetery]], [[Cluj-Napoca]]\n| birth_name    = \n| nickname      = \n| allegiance    = {{Flag|Kingdom of Romania}}\n| branch        = [[Romanian Army|Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1906\u20131945\n| rank          = <!--[[2nd Lieutenant]] (1908)<br>[[1st Lieutenant]] (1911)<br>[[Captain]] (1915)<br>[[Major]] (1917)<br>[[Lieutenant Colonel]] (1923)<br>[[Brigadier General]] (1935)<br>[[Major General]] (1940)<br>[[Lieutenant General]] (1942)<br>-->[[General officer|General]]\n|rank_label       = \n|servicenumber    = \n| unit          = [[16th Doroban\u021bi Regiment]]\n|commands         = \n| battles       =  [[Second Balkan War]]<br>[[World War I]]\n*[[Battle of the Arge\u0219]]\n*[[Battle of M\u0103r\u0103\u0219e\u0219ti]]\n[[World War II]]\n*[[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]]\n*[[Operation M\u00fcnchen]]\n*[[Siege of Sevastopol (1941\u20131942)|Siege of Sevastopol]]\n*[[Battle of the Sea of Azov]]\n*[[Crimean campaign]]\n*[[Jassy\u2013Kishinev Offensive]]\n*[[Battle of Turda]]\n*[[Battle of Debrecen]]\n|battles_label    = \n|memorials        = Bust in [[Cluj-Napoca]]\n|alma_mater       = \n| awards        = [[Order of Michael the Brave]], 3rd Class<br>[[Order of Michael the Brave]], 2nd Class<br>[[Order of Michael the Brave]], 2nd Class (With Swords)<br>[[Order of the Star of Romania]], Knight class<br/>[[Order of the Crown (Romania)]], Grand Officer Class<br>[[Iron Cross]], 2nd Class<br>[[Iron Cross]], 1st Class<br>[[German Cross]], in Gold\n|spouse           = {{marriage|Adela Avramescu|1913}}\n|children         = Felicia Avramescu-Sturdza (1918\u20131945)\n|relations        = \n|laterwork        = \n|signature        = \n|signature_size   = \n|signature_alt    = \n|website          = \n|module           = \n}}\n'''Gheorghe Avramescu''' (26 January 1884 \u2013 3 March 1945) was a Romanian [[Lieutenant General]] during [[World War II]]. In 1945, he was arrested by the [[Soviets]] as \"pro-German.\"<ref name =generals.dk>{{cite web|url=http://www.generals.dk/general/Avramescu/Gheorghe/Romania.html|title=Generals from Romania|publisher=Generals.dk|accessdate=2008-11-24}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nHe was born [[Boto\u0219ani]] on 26 January 1884, and attended the [[A. T. Laurian National College]] between 1898 and 1906. He then enrolled in the Military School of Infantry and Cavalry in [[Bucharest]], graduating in 1908 with the rank of [[second lieutenant]], and being promoted to [[first lieutenant]] in 1911. After serving in the [[Second Balkan War]] in 1913, he was admitted to the [[Carol I National Defence University]], and promoted to captain in 1915. \n\n== World War I and Interwar ==\nWhen Romania entered [[World War I]] in August 1916 on the side of the [[Allies of World War I|Allied powers]], Avramescu fought with the [[Dobruja Army]], under the command of Russian General [[Andrei Zayonchkovski]], and saw action against the German forces of General [[August von Mackensen]]. In November he took command of the 2nd Battalion from the 38th Regiment, and fought in December at the [[Battle of the Arge\u0219]], falling back towards [[Moldavia]] in a series of defensive actions. For his valor in these engagements he was awarded in 1917 the [[Order of the Star of Romania]], Knight class. In the summer of 1917 he fought  at the [[Battle of M\u0103r\u0103\u0219e\u0219ti]]; for his service he was awarded the [[Order of the Crown (Romania)|Order of the Crown]], Grand Officer Class, and was promoted to major on 1 September 1917.\n\nIn the [[interwar period]] he advanced to [[lieutenant colonel]] in 1923, [[colonel]] in 1929, [[brigadier general]] in 1935, and [[major general]] in 1940. At various times, he was in command of the 1st Division [[V\u00e2n\u0103tori de munte]], the 10th Infantry Division, and the III Army Corps.\n\n== World War II ==\nAvramescu served as General Officer Commanding of a number of army units: the 10th Division in 1941, the Mountain Corps in June 1941, the III Corps in October 1943, the VI Corps in February 1944 and [[4th Army (Romania)|4th Army]] from 1944 to 1945.<ref name =generals.dk />\n\nAt the head of the [[V\u00e2n\u0103tori de munte|Mountain Corps]], he participated in [[Operation M\u00fcnchen]], the [[Battle of the Sea of Azov]], [[Crimean campaign]] and [[Siege of Sevastopol (1941\u20131942)|Siege of Sevastopol]]. After the fall of Sevastopol, his Corps occupied [[Crimea]].<ref name=\"adevarul\">{{cite web|url=https://adevarul.ro/locale/botosani/generalul-avramescu-tatuca-soldatilor-romani-doilea-razboi-mondial-disparut-intr-o-operatiune-nkvd-1_591542985ab6550cb807be92/index.html|title=Generalul Avramescu, \u201et\u0103tuca\u201c solda\u0163ilor rom\u00e2ni \u00een al Doilea R\u0103zboi Mondial. A disp\u0103rut \u00eentr-o opera\u0163iune NKVD |first=Cosmin|last=P\u0103tra\u0219cu Zamfirache|newspaper=[[Adev\u0103rul]]|date=May 13, 2017|access-date=April 18, 2020|language=ro}}</ref>\n\nFor his service during the Crimean campaign, Avramescu was promoted on 18 July 1942 to [[lieutenant general]] (''general de corp de armat\u0103''), and was awarded the [[Order of the Crown (Romania)|Order of the Crown]], Grand Officer Class (29 July 1942), the [[Order of Michael the Brave]], 2nd Class (1 September 1942), and the [[German Cross]], in Gold (25 Octomber 1942).\n\nAfter the crushing defeat in the [[Battle of Stalingrad]], in which he didn't participate, the Romanian Army was driven back to its own country during 1943 and the first half of 1944. In August 1944, on the eve of the Soviet [[Jassy\u2013Kishinev Offensive]], he took de facto command of the 4th Army, since general [[Ioan Mihail Racovi\u021b\u0103]] was \"away on leave\" (preparing [[King Michael's Coup]]). Avramescu could not prevent the disastrous defeat, because of the limited number of armored and motorized units at his disposal, and was dismissed on 23 August and replaced by [[Ilie \u0218teflea]].<ref name =worldwar>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldwar2.ro/arr/?article=97|title=The 6th Corps in 1942|website= www.worldwar2.ro}}</ref> \n\nAfter [[King Michael's Coup]], he was recalled to command the [[4th Army (Romania)|4th Army]] on the side of the Soviets against the Germans and Hungarians.  He fought many battles with his 4th Army, including the [[Battle of Turda]] and the [[Battle of Debrecen]]. \n\nAvramescu complained repeatedly to the Soviets about the lack of supplies and impossible tasks for his Army. For this, he was relieved of command on 11 January 1945, and put on reserve. Nevertheless, he was promoted to [[general officer|general]] on 9 February and recalled to duty.<ref name =generals.dk /><ref name =worldwar />  Returning to the front, he successfully led the 4th Army in the first phase of the [[Zvolen]]\u2013[[Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica]] offensive in [[Slovakia]].\n\n==Death==\nOn 2 March 1945, when on the [[Slovakia]]n front, General Avramescu was summoned by the commander of the [[40th Army (Soviet Union)|40th Soviet Army]].<ref name=\"Historia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.historia.ro/sectiune/general/articol/generalul-avramescu-tradator-sau-victima-a-nkvd|title=Generalul Avramescu, tr\u0103d\u0103tor sau victim\u0103 a NKVD?|magazine=[[Historia (magazine)|Historia]]|first=Manuel|last= St\u0103nescu| language=Romanian|access-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref> After one hour, the Romanian delegation was told that Avramescu and Russian general Filip Fedorovici Jmacenko left for the command point of Ukrainian Front 2, as they were expected there by Marshal [[Rodion Malinovsky]], leading later commentators to assert General Avramescu was arrested. \n\n[[File:Cluj-Napoca-Piata \u0218tefan cel Mare-bustul,Gheorghe V. Avramescu-IMG 7102.jpg|thumb|left|200px| Bust of Avramescu in \"\u0218tefan cel Mare\" Square, Cluj-Napoca]]\n\nThe Romanian 4th Army was placed under command of general [[Nicolae D\u0103sc\u0103lescu]], who struggled to find out what had happened to general Avr\u0103mescu. Soviet general [[Filipp Zhmachenko]] advised him to find information about Avramescu at the Romanian Ministry of Defence or the Romanian General Staff. Avramescu was killed on March 3, 1945 in an aerial attack on the car which transported him, and his body was buried in [[Budapest]]'s Soshalom cemetery. The general was the only occupant of the car to be killed.  According to the official report issued on March 23, 1945 by [[NKVD]] head [[Lavrentiy Beria]], Avramescu was hit by a bullet through the car's windshield.<ref name=\"adevarul\"/>\n\nAlso on 3 March 1945, Adela, Avramescu's wife and Felicia Avramescu-Sturdza, his daughter, were arrested and sent to [[Siberia]]. His daughter committed suicide; according to Soviet sources, this happened on 6 March 1945.<ref name=\"Historia\" /> Adela returned to Romania in 1956. \n\nOn 23 October 2000, his remains were brought back to Romania and were reburied with military honours at the [[Hajongard cemetery]] of [[Cluj-Napoca]]. A bust of Avramescu has been erected in the city's \"\u0218tefan cel Mare\" Square.\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{Cite book\n  |last1=Patzwall\n  |first1=Klaus D.\n  |last2=Scherzer\n  |first2=Veit\n  |year=2001\n  |title=Das Deutsche Kreuz 1941 \u2013 1945 Geschichte und Inhaber Band II\n  |trans-title=The German Cross 1941 \u2013 1945 History and Recipients Volume 2\n  |language=German\n  |location=Norderstedt, Germany\n  |publisher=Verlag Klaus D. Patzwall\n  |isbn=978-3-931533-45-8\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Avramescu, Gheorghe}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1945 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Boto\u0219ani]]\n[[Category:Carol I National Defence University alumni]]\n[[Category:Romanian Land Forces generals]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel of the Second Balkan War]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Michael the Brave]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Michael the Brave, 2nd class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Star of Romania]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Crown (Romania)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gold German Cross]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Iron Cross, 1st class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Iron Cross, 2nd class]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Gheorghe Avramescu\n| image         = Gheorghe Avramescu.jpg\n| caption       = Avramescu in 1945\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1884|01|26|df=yes}}\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1945|03|03|1884|01|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Boto\u0219ani]], [[Boto\u0219ani County]], [[Kingdom of Romania]]\n| death_place  = [[J\u00e1szber\u00e9ny]], [[Kingdom of Hungary]]\n| placeofburial = [[Hajongard cemetery]], [[Cluj-Napoca]]\n| birth_name    = \n| nickname      = \n| allegiance    = {{Flag|Kingdom of Romania}}\n| branch        = [[Romanian Army|Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1906\u20131945\n| rank          = <!--[[2nd Lieutenant]] (1908)<br>[[1st Lieutenant]] (1911)<br>[[Captain]] (1915)<br>[[Major]] (1917)<br>[[Lieutenant Colonel]] (1923)<br>[[Brigadier General]] (1935)<br>[[Major General]] (1940)<br>[[Lieutenant General]] (1942)<br>-->[[General officer|General]]\n|rank_label       = \n|servicenumber    = \n| unit          = [[16th Doroban\u021bi Regiment]]\n|commands         = \n| battles       =  [[Second Balkan War]]<br>[[World War I]]\n*[[Battle of the Arge\u0219]]\n*[[Battle of M\u0103r\u0103\u0219e\u0219ti]]\n[[World War II]]\n*[[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]]\n*[[Operation M\u00fcnchen]]\n*[[Siege of Sevastopol (1941\u20131942)|Siege of Sevastopol]]\n*[[Battle of the Sea of Azov]]\n*[[Crimean campaign]]\n*[[Jassy\u2013Kishinev Offensive]]\n*[[Battle of Turda]]\n*[[Battle of Debrecen]]\n|battles_label    = \n|awards           = \n|memorials        = Bust in [[Cluj-Napoca]]\n|alma_mater       = \n| awards        = [[Order of Michael the Brave]], 3rd Class<br>[[Order of Michael the Brave]], 2nd Class<br>[[Order of Michael the Brave]], 2nd Class (With Swords)<br>[[Order of the Star of Romania]], Knight class</br>[[Order of the Crown (Romania)]], Grand Officer Class<br>[[Iron Cross]], 2nd Class<br>[[Iron Cross]], 1st Class<br>[[German Cross]], in Gold\n|spouse           = {{marriage|Adela Avramescu|1913}}\n|children         = Felicia Avramescu-Sturdza (1918\u20131945)\n|relations        = \n|laterwork        = \n|signature        = \n|signature_size   = \n|signature_alt    = \n|website          = \n|module           = \n}}\n'''Gheorghe Avramescu''' (26 January 1884 \u2013 3 March 1945) was a Romanian [[Lieutenant General]] during [[World War II]]. In 1945, he was arrested by the [[Soviets]] as \"pro-German.\"<ref name =generals.dk>{{cite web|url=http://www.generals.dk/general/Avramescu/Gheorghe/Romania.html|title=Generals from Romania|publisher=Generals.dk|accessdate=2008-11-24}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nHe was born [[Boto\u0219ani]] on 26 January 1884, and attended the [[A. T. Laurian National College]] between 1898 and 1906. He then enrolled in the Military School of Infantry and Cavalry in [[Bucharest]], graduating in 1908 with the rank of [[second lieutenant]], and being promoted to [[first lieutenant]] in 1911. After serving in the [[Second Balkan War]] in 1913, he was admitted to the [[Carol I National Defence University]], and promoted to captain in 1915. \n\n== World War I and Interwar ==\nWhen Romania entered [[World War I]] in August 1916 on the side of the [[Allies of World War I|Allied powers]], Avramescu fought with the [[Dobruja Army]], under the command of Russian General [[Andrei Zayonchkovski]], and saw action against the German forces of General [[August von Mackensen]]. In November he took command of the 2nd Battalion from the 38th Regiment, and fought in December at the [[Battle of the Arge\u0219]], falling back towards [[Moldavia]] in a series of defensive actions. For his valor in these engagements he was awarded in 1917 the [[Order of the Star of Romania]], Knight class. In the summer of 1917 he fought  at the [[Battle of M\u0103r\u0103\u0219e\u0219ti]]; for his service he was awarded the [[Order of the Crown (Romania)|Order of the Crown]], Grand Officer Class, and was promoted to major on 1 September 1917.\n\nIn the [[interwar period]] he advanced to [[lieutenant colonel]] in 1923, [[colonel]] in 1929, [[brigadier general]] in 1935, and [[major general]] in 1940. At various times, he was in command of the 1st Division [[V\u00e2n\u0103tori de munte]], the 10th Infantry Division, and the III Army Corps.\n\n== World War II ==\nAvramescu served as General Officer Commanding of a number of army units: the 10th Division in 1941, the Mountain Corps in June 1941, the III Corps in October 1943, the VI Corps in February 1944 and [[4th Army (Romania)|4th Army]] from 1944 to 1945.<ref name =generals.dk />\n\nAt the head of the [[V\u00e2n\u0103tori de munte|Mountain Corps]], he participated in [[Operation M\u00fcnchen]], the [[Battle of the Sea of Azov]], [[Crimean campaign]] and [[Siege of Sevastopol (1941\u20131942)|Siege of Sevastopol]]. After the fall of Sevastopol, his Corps occupied [[Crimea]].<ref name=\"adevarul\">{{cite web|url=https://adevarul.ro/locale/botosani/generalul-avramescu-tatuca-soldatilor-romani-doilea-razboi-mondial-disparut-intr-o-operatiune-nkvd-1_