ebruary and recalled to duty.<ref name =generals.dk /><ref name =worldwar />  Returning to the front, he successfully led the 4th Army in the first phase of the [[Zvolen]]\u2013[[Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica]] offensive in [[Slovakia]].\n\n==Death==\nOn 2 March 1945, when on the [[Slovakia]]n front, General Avramescu was summoned by the commander of the [[40th Army (Soviet Union)|40th Soviet Army]].<ref name=\"Historia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.historia.ro/sectiune/general/articol/generalul-avramescu-tradator-sau-victima-a-nkvd|title=Generalul Avramescu, tr\u0103d\u0103tor sau victim\u0103 a NKVD?|magazine=[[Historia (magazine)|Historia]]|first=Manuel|last= St\u0103nescu| language=Romanian|access-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref> After one hour, the Romanian delegation was told that Avramescu and Russian general Filip Fedorovici Jmacenko left for the command point of Ukrainian Front 2, as they were expected there by Marshal [[Rodion Malinovsky]], leading later commentators to assert General Avramescu was arrested. \n\n[[File:Cluj-Napoca-Piata \u0218tefan cel Mare-bustul,Gheorghe V. Avramescu-IMG 7102.jpg|thumb|left|200px| Bust of Avramescu in \"\u0218tefan cel Mare\" Square, Cluj-Napoca]]\n\nThe Romanian 4th Army was placed under command of general [[Nicolae D\u0103sc\u0103lescu]], who struggled to find out what had happened to general Avr\u0103mescu. Soviet general [[Filipp Zhmachenko]] advised him to find information about Avramescu at the Romanian Ministry of Defence or the Romanian General Staff. Avramescu was killed on March 3, 1945 in an aerial attack on the car which transported him, and his body was buried in [[Budapest]]'s Soshalom cemetery. The general was the only occupant of the car to be killed.  According to the official report issued on March 23, 1945 by [[NKVD]] head [[Lavrentiy Beria]], Avramescu was hit by a bullet through the car's windshield.<ref name=\"adevarul\"/>\n\nAlso on 3 March 1945, Adela, Avramescu's wife and Felicia Avramescu-Sturdza, his daughter, were arrested and sent to [[Siberia]]. His daughter committed suicide; according to Soviet sources, this happened on 6 March 1945.<ref name=\"Historia\" /> Adela returned to Romania in 1956. \n\nOn 23 October 2000, his remains were brought back to Romania and were reburied with military honours at the [[Hajongard cemetery]] of [[Cluj-Napoca]]. A bust of Avramescu has been erected in the city's \"\u0218tefan cel Mare\" Square.\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{Cite book\n  |last1=Patzwall\n  |first1=Klaus D.\n  |last2=Scherzer\n  |first2=Veit\n  |year=2001\n  |title=Das Deutsche Kreuz 1941 \u2013 1945 Geschichte und Inhaber Band II\n  |trans-title=The German Cross 1941 \u2013 1945 History and Recipients Volume 2\n  |language=German\n  |location=Norderstedt, Germany\n  |publisher=Verlag Klaus D. Patzwall\n  |isbn=978-3-931533-45-8\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Avramescu, Gheorghe}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1945 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Boto\u0219ani]]\n[[Category:Carol I National Defence University alumni]]\n[[Category:Romanian Land Forces generals]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel of the Second Balkan War]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Michael the Brave]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Michael the Brave, 2nd class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Star of Romania]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Crown (Romania)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gold German Cross]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Iron Cross, 1st class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Iron Cross, 2nd class]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 -WP:WCWproject (Tag with incorrect syntax - Duplicate arguments in template calls)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gheorghe_Avramescu"}
{"title_page": "Hanunuo script", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2019}}\n{{Short description|Abugida indigenous to Mindoro, Philippines}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2019}}\n{{Contains special characters\n| special    = uncommon [[Unicode]] characters\n| fix        = Help:Multilingual support\n| image      = Replacement character.svg\n| link       = Specials (Unicode block)#Replacement character\n| alt        = <?>\n| compact    = yes\n}}\n\n{{Infobox writing system\n |name=Hanun\u00f3'o <br>(Mangyan Baybayin/Surat Mangyan)\n |altname={{script|Hano|\u1731\u1728\u1733\u1728\u1733\u1722}}\n |type=[[Abugida]]\n |languages=[[Hanun\u00f3'o language|Hanun\u00f3'o]]\n|fam1=[[Proto-Sinaitic script]]\n|fam2=[[Phoenician alphabet]]\n|fam3=[[Aramaic alphabet]]\n|fam4=[[Brahmi script|Br\u0101hm\u012b]]\n|fam5=[[Pallava alphabet|Pallava]]\n|fam6=[[Kawi script|Kawi]]\n|sisters='''In the Philippines:'''<br/>\n[[Buhid script|Buhid (Mangyan Baybayin, Surat Mangyan)]]<br/>\n[[Kulitan script|Kulitan (Kapampangan Baybayin, Surat Kapampangan)]]<br/>\n[[Tagbanwa script|Tagbanwa (Tagbanwa Baybayin/Apurahuano)]]<br/>\n[[Palawan languages|Ibalnan (Palaw'an Baybayin)]]<br/><br/>'''In other countries:'''<br/>[[Balinese_script|Balinese]]<br/>[[Batak_script|Batak]]<br/>[[Javanese_script|Javanese]]<br/>[[Lontara_script|Lontara]]<br/>[[Sundanese_script|Sundanese]]<br/>[[Rencong_script|Rencong]]<br/>[[Rejang_script|Rejang]]\n |time=c. 1300&ndash;present\n |unicode=[https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U1720.pdf U+1720&ndash;U+173F]\n |iso15924=Hano\n |sample= Hanunoo script sample.svg\n |imagesize= 220px\n |note=none\n}}\n'''Hanunoo''' ({{IPA-tl|hanunu\u0294\u0254|IPA}}), also rendered '''Hanun\u00f3'o''', is one of the scripts [[ancient Philippine scripts|indigenous to the Philippines]] and is used by the [[Mangyan peoples]] of southern [[Mindoro]] to write the [[Hanun\u00f3'o language]].<ref>http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/985669/protect-all-ph-writing-systems-heritage-advocates-urge-congress</ref><ref name=\"Postma\">{{cite journal\n  | first=Antoon\n  | last=Postma\n  | title=Contemporary Mangyan Scripts\n  | journal=Philippine Journal of Linguistics\n  | volume=2\n  | issue=1\n  |date=July 1971\n  | pages=1\u201312}}</ref>\n\nIt is an [[abugida]] descended from the [[Brahmic scripts]], closely related to [[Baybayin|Sulat Tagalog]], and is famous for being written vertical but written upward, rather than downward as nearly all other scripts (however, it's read horizontally left to right). It is usually written on bamboo by incising characters with a knife.<ref name=\"Rubino\">{{cite web\n  | last=Rubino\n  | first=Carl\n  | title=The Hanunoo Script\n  | work=Ancient Scripts of the Philippines\n  | url=http://iloko.tripod.com/Hanunoo.html\n  | accessdate=2016-10-08}}\n</ref><ref name=\"Conklin\"/> Most known Hanun\u00f3'o inscriptions are relatively recent because of the perishable nature of bamboo. It is therefore difficult to trace the history of the script.<ref name=\"Postma\"/>\n\n==Structure==\nFifteen basic characters of the Hanun\u00f3'o script each represent one of the fifteen consonants {{IPA|/p/ /t/ /k/ /b/ /d/ /\u0261/ /m/ /n/ /\u014b/ /l/ /r/ /s/ /h/ /j/ /w/}} followed by the inherent vowel {{IPA|/a/}}.<ref name=\"Conklin\">{{cite book\n  | first=Harold C.\n  | last=Conklin\n  | title=Fine Description: Ethnographic and Linguistic Essays\n  | year=2007\n  | publisher=Yale University Southeast Asia Studies\n  | location=New Haven\n  | pages=320\u2013342}}</ref> Other syllables are written by modifying each of these characters with one of two [[diacritics]] ''(kudlit)'' which change the vowel sound to /i/ or /u/.<ref name=\"Rubino\"/>  The glyph for /la/ is the same as that for /ra/ but the glyphs for /li/ and /ri/ are distinct, as are those for /lu/ and /ru/.  There are also three glyphs that represent vowels which stand alone (phonetically preceded by a [[glottal stop]], written q in Roman transliteration).<ref name=\"Daniels\">{{cite book\n  | first=Peter\n  | last=Daniels\n  |author2=William Bright\n  | title=The World's Writing Systems\n  | year=1996\n  | publisher=Oxford University Press\n  | location=New York\n  | pages=481\u2013484}}\n</ref> [[Syllable coda|Final consonants]] are not written, and so must be determined from context.<ref name=\"Rubino\"/>\nDutch anthropologist [[Antoon Postma]], who went to the Philippines from the Netherlands in the 1950s, introduced the ''pamudpod'' sign ({{spaces|2}}{{Script|Hano| \u1734}} ) to indicate a syllable final consonant.<ref name=\"UniStdIndonesiaAndOceania\"/>  (The pamudpod functions as a [[virama]].)\n\n{|border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" class=\"wikitable nounderlines\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;background:#FFFFFF;font-size:large;text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | Hanun\u00f3'o Vowels\n|-\n! \n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | Initial\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | Dependent\n|-style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\"\n| [[Orthographic transcription|transcription]] || a || i || u || i || u\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | letter\n| title=\"U+1720: HANUNOO LETTER A\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1720}}\n| title=\"U+1721: HANUNOO LETTER I\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1721}}\n| title=\"U+1722: HANUNOO LETTER U\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1722}}\n| title=\"U+1732: HANUNOO VOWEL SIGN I\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1732}}\n| title=\"U+1733: HANUNOO VOWEL SIGN U\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1733}}\n|}\n\n{|border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" class=\"wikitable nounderlines\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;background:#FFFFFF;font-size:large;text-align:center\"\n| colspan=\"19\" style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | '''Hanun\u00f3'o Syllables'''<ref name=\"UniStdIndonesiaAndOceania\"/>\n|-style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\"\n| transcription || k || g || ng || t || d || n || p || b || m || y || r || l || w || s || h\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | consonant + a\n| title=\"U+1723: HANUNOO LETTER KA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1723}}\n| title=\"U+1724: HANUNOO LETTER GA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1724}}\n| title=\"U+1725: HANUNOO LETTER NGA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1725}}\n| title=\"U+1726: HANUNOO LETTER TA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1726}}\n| title=\"U+1727: HANUNOO LETTER DA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1727}}\n| title=\"U+1728: HANUNOO LETTER NA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1728}}\n| title=\"U+1729: HANUNOO LETTER PA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1729}}\n| title=\"U+172A: HANUNOO LETTER BA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172a}}\n| title=\"U+172B: HANUNOO LETTER MA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172b}}\n| title=\"U+172C: HANUNOO LETTER YA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172c}}\n| title=\"U+172D: HANUNOO LETTER RA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172d}}\n| title=\"U+172E: HANUNOO LETTER LA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172e}}\n| title=\"U+172F: HANUNOO LETTER WA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172f}}\n| title=\"U+1730: HANUNOO LETTER SA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1730}}\n| title=\"U+1731: HANUNOO LETTER HA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1731}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | consonant + i\n| title=\"KI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1723\u1732}}\n| title=\"GI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1724\u1732}}\n| title=\"NGI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1725\u1732}}\n| title=\"TI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1726\u1732}}\n| title=\"DI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1727\u1732}}\n| title=\"NI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1728\u1732}}\n| title=\"PI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1729\u1732}}\n| title=\"BI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172a\u1732}}\n| title=\"MI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172b\u1732}}\n| title=\"YI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172c\u1732}}\n| title=\"RI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172d\u1732}}\n| title=\"LI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172e\u1732}}\n| title=\"WI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172f\u1732}}\n| title=\"SI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1730\u1732}}\n| title=\"HI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1731\u1732}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | consonant + u\n| title=\"KU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1723\u1733}}\n| title=\"GU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1724\u1733}}\n| title=\"NGU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1725\u1733}}\n| title=\"TU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1726\u1733}}\n| title=\"DU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1727\u1733}}\n| title=\"NU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1728\u1733}}\n| title=\"PU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1729\u1733}}\n| title=\"BU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172a\u1733}}\n| title=\"MU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172b\u1733}}\n| title=\"YU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172c\u1733}}\n| title=\"RU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172d\u1733}}\n| title=\"LU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172e\u1733}}\n| title=\"WU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172f\u1733}}\n| title=\"SU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1730\u1733}}\n| title=\"HU\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1731\u1733}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | with pamudpod\n| title=\"-K\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1723\u1734}}\n| title=\"-G\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1724\u1734}}\n| title=\"-NG\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1725\u1734}}\n| title=\"-T\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1726\u1734}}\n| title=\"-D\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1727\u1734}}\n| title=\"-N\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1728\u1734}}\n| title=\"-P\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1729\u1734}}\n| title=\"-B\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172a\u1734}}\n| title=\"-M\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172b\u1734}}\n| title=\"-Y\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172c\u1734}}\n| title=\"-R\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172d\u1734}}\n| title=\"-L\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172e\u1734}}\n| title=\"-W\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172f\u1734}}\n| title=\"-S\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1730\u1734}}\n| title=\"-H\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1731\u1734}}\n|}\n\nNote: With the proper [[Help:Multilingual support#Hanun\u00f3'o|rendering support]], the Hanun\u00f3'o syllable NGU above ({{Script|Hano|\u1725\u1733}}) should resemble an italic ''V'' joined with two short, parallel diagonal lines ( \\\\ ).\n\nThe script makes use of single ( {{Script|Hano|\u1735}} ) and double ( {{Script|Hano|\u1736}} ) [[danda]] punctuation characters.<ref name=\"UniStdIndonesiaAndOceania\">{{cite web|url=https://www.unicode.org/versions/Unicode13.0.0/ch17.pdf#G26723|title=Chapter 17: Indonesia and Oceania|publisher=Unicode Consortium|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Direction of writing==\n[[File:Hanunoo-Mangyan Alternative Letters Ra Wu.jpg|thumb|Hanun\u00f3'o alternative letters Ra and Wu.]]\n[[File:Bayi, a bamboo bow from Mindoro.jpg|thumb|A bow from [[Oriental Mindoro]] made of bamboo, locally called ''Bayi'' ({{Script|Hano|\u172a\u172c\u1732}}), inscribed with Hanun\u00f3'o script.]]\nThe Hanun\u00f3'o script is conventionally written away from the body (from bottom to top) in columns which go from left to right.<ref name=\"Rubino\"/> Within the columns, characters may have any orientation but the orientation must be consistent for all characters in a text. The characters are typically vertical with the /i/ diacritic on the left and the /u/ on the right, or horizontal with the /i/ on the top and the /u/ on the bottom.<ref name=\"Daniels\"/> Left-handed people often write in mirror image, which reverses both the direction of writing (right to left instead of left to right) and the characters themselves.<ref name=\"Conklin\"/>\n\n==Learning the script==\nYoung Hanun\u00f3'o men and women (called ''layqaw'') learn the script primarily in order to memorize love songs. The goal is to learn as many songs as possible, and using the script to write the songs facilitates this process.  The script is also used to write letters, notifications, and other documents. The characters are not memorized in any particular order; learners typically begin by learning how to write their name. Literacy among the Hanun\u00f3'o people is high despite a lack of formal education in the script.<ref name=\"Conklin\"/>\n\n== Unicode ==\n{{Main article|Hanunoo (Unicode block)}}\nThe [[Unicode]] range for Hanun\u00f3'o  is U+1720&ndash;U+173F:\n\n{{Unicode chart Hanunoo}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Baybayin]]\n*[[Buhid script]]\n*[[Tagbanwa alphabet]]\n*[[Kawi script]]\n*[[Filipino orthography]]\n*[[Kulitan (Kapampangan Writing Script)|Kulitan]]\n*See [[Help:Multilingual_support#Hanun.C3.B3.27o|multilingual support]] for fonts supporting Hanun\u00f3'o\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://iloko.tripod.com/hanuscript.gif The Entire Hanun\u00f3o script]\n*[http://www.omniglot.com/writing/hanunoo.htm Hanun\u00f3o script written clearly]\n\n{{Kawi family}}\n{{list of writing systems}}\n{{Philippine scripts}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hanuno'o Script}}\n[[Category:Brahmic scripts]]\n[[Category:Philippine scripts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2019}}\n{{Short description|Abugida indigenous to Mindoro, Philippines}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2019}}\n{{Contains special characters\n| special    = uncommon [[Unicode]] characters\n| fix        = Help:Multilingual support\n| image      = Replacement character.svg\n| link       = Specials (Unicode block)#Replacement character\n| alt        = <?>\n| compact    = yes\n}}\n\n{{Infobox writing system\n |name=Hanun\u00f3'o <br>(Mangyan Baybayin/Surat Mangyan)</br>\n |altname={{script|Hano|\u1731\u1728\u1733\u1728\u1733\u1722}}\n |type=[[Abugida]]\n |languages=[[Hanun\u00f3'o language|Hanun\u00f3'o]]\n|fam1=[[Proto-Sinaitic script]]\n|fam2=[[Phoenician alphabet]]\n|fam3=[[Aramaic alphabet]]\n|fam4=[[Brahmi script|Br\u0101hm\u012b]]\n|fam5=[[Pallava alphabet|Pallava]]\n|fam6=[[Kawi script|Kawi]]\n|sisters='''In the Philippines:'''<br/>\n[[Buhid script|Buhid (Mangyan Baybayin, Surat Mangyan)]]<br/>\n[[Kulitan script|Kulitan (Kapampangan Baybayin, Surat Kapampangan)]]<br/>\n[[Tagbanwa script|Tagbanwa (Tagbanwa Baybayin/Apurahuano)]]</br>\n[[Palawan languages|Ibalnan (Palaw'an Baybayin)]]</br><br/>'''In other countries:'''<br/>[[Balinese_script|Balinese]]<br/>[[Batak_script|Batak]]<br/>[[Javanese_script|Javanese]]<br/>[[Lontara_script|Lontara]]<br/>[[Sundanese_script|Sundanese]]<br/>[[Rencong_script|Rencong]]<br/>[[Rejang_script|Rejang]]\n |time=c. 1300&ndash;present\n |unicode=[https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U1720.pdf U+1720&ndash;U+173F]\n |iso15924=Hano\n |sample= Hanunoo script sample.svg\n |imagesize= 220px\n |note=none\n}}\n'''Hanunoo''' ({{IPA-tl|hanunu\u0294\u0254|IPA}}), also rendered '''Hanun\u00f3'o''', is one of the scripts [[ancient Philippine scripts|indigenous to the Philippines]] and is used by the [[Mangyan peoples]] of southern [[Mindoro]] to write the [[Hanun\u00f3'o language]].<ref>http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/985669/protect-all-ph-writing-systems-heritage-advocates-urge-congress</ref><ref name=\"Postma\">{{cite journal\n  | first=Antoon\n  | last=Postma\n  | title=Contemporary Mangyan Scripts\n  | journal=Philippine Journal of Linguistics\n  | volume=2\n  | issue=1\n  |date=July 1971\n  | pages=1\u201312}}</ref>\n\nIt is an [[abugida]] descended from the [[Brahmic scripts]], closely related to [[Baybayin|Sulat Tagalog]], and is famous for being written vertical but written upward, rather than downward as nearly all other scripts (however, it's read horizontally left to right). It is usually written on bamboo by incising characters with a knife.<ref name=\"Rubino\">{{cite web\n  | last=Rubino\n  | first=Carl\n  | title=The Hanunoo Script\n  | work=Ancient Scripts of the Philippines\n  | url=http://iloko.tripod.com/Hanunoo.html\n  | accessdate=2016-10-08}}\n</ref><ref name=\"Conklin\"/> Most known Hanun\u00f3'o inscriptions are relatively recent because of the perishable nature of bamboo. It is therefore difficult to trace the history of the script.<ref name=\"Postma\"/>\n\n==Structure==\nFifteen basic characters of the Hanun\u00f3'o script each represent one of the fifteen consonants {{IPA|/p/ /t/ /k/ /b/ /d/ /\u0261/ /m/ /n/ /\u014b/ /l/ /r/ /s/ /h/ /j/ /w/}} followed by the inherent vowel {{IPA|/a/}}.<ref name=\"Conklin\">{{cite book\n  | first=Harold C.\n  | last=Conklin\n  | title=Fine Description: Ethnographic and Linguistic Essays\n  | year=2007\n  | publisher=Yale University Southeast Asia Studies\n  | location=New Haven\n  | pages=320\u2013342}}</ref> Other syllables are written by modifying each of these characters with one of two [[diacritics]] ''(kudlit)'' which change the vowel sound to /i/ or /u/.<ref name=\"Rubino\"/>  The glyph for /la/ is the same as that for /ra/ but the glyphs for /li/ and /ri/ are distinct, as are those for /lu/ and /ru/.  There are also three glyphs that represent vowels which stand alone (phonetically preceded by a [[glottal stop]], written q in Roman transliteration).<ref name=\"Daniels\">{{cite book\n  | first=Peter\n  | last=Daniels\n  |author2=William Bright\n  | title=The World's Writing Systems\n  | year=1996\n  | publisher=Oxford University Press\n  | location=New York\n  | pages=481\u2013484}}\n</ref> [[Syllable coda|Final consonants]] are not written, and so must be determined from context.<ref name=\"Rubino\"/>\nDutch anthropologist [[Antoon Postma]], who went to the Philippines from the Netherlands in the 1950s, introduced the ''pamudpod'' sign ({{spaces|2}}{{Script|Hano| \u1734}} ) to indicate a syllable final consonant.<ref name=\"UniStdIndonesiaAndOceania\"/>  (The pamudpod functions as a [[virama]].)\n\n{|border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" class=\"wikitable nounderlines\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;background:#FFFFFF;font-size:large;text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | Hanun\u00f3'o Vowels\n|-\n! \n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | Initial\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | Dependent\n|-style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\"\n| [[Orthographic transcription|transcription]] || a || i || u || i || u\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | letter\n| title=\"U+1720: HANUNOO LETTER A\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1720}}\n| title=\"U+1721: HANUNOO LETTER I\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1721}}\n| title=\"U+1722: HANUNOO LETTER U\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1722}}\n| title=\"U+1732: HANUNOO VOWEL SIGN I\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1732}}\n| title=\"U+1733: HANUNOO VOWEL SIGN U\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1733}}\n|}\n\n{|border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" class=\"wikitable nounderlines\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;background:#FFFFFF;font-size:large;text-align:center\"\n| colspan=\"19\" style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | '''Hanun\u00f3'o Syllables'''<ref name=\"UniStdIndonesiaAndOceania\"/>\n|-style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\"\n| transcription || k || g || ng || t || d || n || p || b || m || y || r || l || w || s || h\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | consonant + a\n| title=\"U+1723: HANUNOO LETTER KA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1723}}\n| title=\"U+1724: HANUNOO LETTER GA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1724}}\n| title=\"U+1725: HANUNOO LETTER NGA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1725}}\n| title=\"U+1726: HANUNOO LETTER TA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1726}}\n| title=\"U+1727: HANUNOO LETTER DA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1727}}\n| title=\"U+1728: HANUNOO LETTER NA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1728}}\n| title=\"U+1729: HANUNOO LETTER PA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1729}}\n| title=\"U+172A: HANUNOO LETTER BA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172a}}\n| title=\"U+172B: HANUNOO LETTER MA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172b}}\n| title=\"U+172C: HANUNOO LETTER YA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172c}}\n| title=\"U+172D: HANUNOO LETTER RA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172d}}\n| title=\"U+172E: HANUNOO LETTER LA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172e}}\n| title=\"U+172F: HANUNOO LETTER WA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172f}}\n| title=\"U+1730: HANUNOO LETTER SA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1730}}\n| title=\"U+1731: HANUNOO LETTER HA\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1731}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F8F8F8;font-size:small\" | consonant + i\n| title=\"KI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1723\u1732}}\n| title=\"GI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1724\u1732}}\n| title=\"NGI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1725\u1732}}\n| title=\"TI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1726\u1732}}\n| title=\"DI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1727\u1732}}\n| title=\"NI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1728\u1732}}\n| title=\"PI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u1729\u1732}}\n| title=\"BI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172a\u1732}}\n| title=\"MI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172b\u1732}}\n| title=\"YI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172c\u1732}}\n| title=\"RI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172d\u1732}}\n| title=\"LI\" | {{Script|Hano|\u172e\u1732}}\